To set the text color to red in CSS, you use the **`color`** property. You can specify the color using a named keyword, a hex code, an RGB value, or other color formats.

Here are the most common ways to do it:

### 1. Using a Named Color (Simplest)
```css
p {
  color: red;
}
```

### 2. Using a Hex Code (More precise control)
```css
p {
  color: #ff0000;
}
```

### 3. Using RGB Values
```css
p {
  color: rgb(255, 0, 0);
}
```

### Example in Context
If you want to apply this to a specific class in your HTML:

**CSS:**
```css
.error-text {
  color: red;
}
```

**HTML:**
```html
<p class="error-text">This text will appear in red.</p>
```

You can place these rules in an external `.css` file, inside a `<style>` tag in your HTML `<head>`, or directly in an element's `style` attribute (e.g., `<p style="color: red;">`).

